"CASE Report on Support of Colleges and Universities" (NASA Form 1356).\n2. "Individual Procurement Action Report" (NASA Form 507).\nTherefore, other sources should be used for completing Forms 507 or 1356.\n\nNASA\'S UNIVERSITY PROGRAM\nACTIVE GRANTS AND RESEARCH CONTRACTS\nFISCAL YEAR 1975\n\nNational Aeronautics and Space Administration\nOffice of University Affairs\nWashington, D.C. 20546\n\nAcknowledgements\nThis report was developed in the Policy Coordination Division of the Office of University\nAffairs under the guidance of W. A. Greene, Chief. Preparation of the input data for processing\nwas accomplished by Doris J. Goodwin, ADP Systems Supervisor. The Scientific and Technical\nInformation Office produced the reproduction masters on the Photon Computer.\nAdditional Copies\nFor sale by the Superintendent of Documents, U.S. Government Printing Office\nWashington, D.C. 20402 \xe2\x80\xa2 Price 84.70\nStock Number 038-000-00636-5\n\nFOREWORD\n\nAs basic policy NASA believes that colleges and universities should be encouraged to participate in\nthe nation\'s space and aeronautics program to the maximum extent practicable. Indeed, universities\nare considered as partners with government and industry in the nation\'s aerospace program. NASA\'s\nobjective is to have them bring their scientific, engineering, and social research competence to bear\non aerospace problems and on the broader social, economic, and international implications of\nNASA\'s technical and scientific programs. It is expected that, in so doing, universities will strengthen\nboth their research and their educational capabilities to contribute more effectively to the national\nwell-being.\nNASA Field Centers and certain Headquarters Program Offices provide funds for those R&D\nactivities in universities which contribute to the mission needs of that particular NASA element.\nAlthough NASA has no predetermined amount of money to devote to university activities, the\neffort funded each year is substantial. (See the bar chart on the next page). This annual report is\none means of documenting the NASA-university relationship, frequently denoted, collectively, as\nNASA\'s University Program.\nThe Office of University Affairs (OUA) serves as a focal point for NASA\'s relationships with\ncolleges and universities. One of its roles is to provide information on the NASA University\nProgram. The present document is designed to serve several purposes and a wide range of audiences\nfrom private individuals to NASA employees. The emphasis is on the technical content of the\nprogram, rather than on fiscal data, which is available separately from OUA. As some terminology\nwill not be familiar to all readers, a "User\'s Guide" is included to facilitate the fullest use of the\nmaterial related to the interests of any particular reader.\nInformation on obtaining reports resulting from these projects may be obtained from:\nScientific and Technical Information Office, Code KS, Washington, DC 20546.\n\xe2\x80\xa2\n\n7\n\nrank D. (P is the Office of University Affairs.)\nA full listing of the suffix letters and information on NASA\'s organizational structure may be found\nin the NASA Headquarters Telephone Directory. (The Directory is for sale by the Superintendent of\nDocuments, U.S. Government Printing Office, Washington, D.C. 20402.)\n\nIII. CASE Fields of Science and Engineering\nThe National Science Foundation (NSF) on behalf of the Committee on Academic Science and\nEngineering (CASE) of the Federal Council for Science and Technology (FCST) operates a\ngovernment-wide system for collecting and analyzing data on support to colleges and universities.\nParticipating agencies report annually to NSF which in turn issues Support to Universities, Colleges\nand Selected Nonprofit Institutions. The CASE Fields, used in the extensive tabulations contained in\nthat document, form the only consistent classification system for government sponsored research.\nThe fields are listed in full in Appendix B.\n\nIV. Cross-Indexes\nThe cross-indexed Appendices are related to the citations (descriptions) by the accession number\n(item 3). The accession number has meaning only in this report; it is in no way permanently associated\nwith nor does it uniquely identify a specific grant or contract anywhere except in the present report.\nAccession numbers are assigned sequentially to the citations, beginning with 1000. Thus, when an\nentry of interest is identified in any one of the Appendices, the associated accession number allows\nready location of the full description in the body of the report.\nAppendix A - Given only the grant or contract number this index enables the reader\nto locate the citation. The first page tells how to distinguish grants\nfrom contracts.\nAppendix B - This index provides rapid access to all projects in a particular area of\nendeavor, as defined by the CASE Fields. This listing is also easily\nused to determine the institutions and principal investigators conducting\nNASA projects in a field.\nAppendix C - The types of effort sponsored by each NASA installation may be\ndetermined from this index.\nAppendix D - This index is included primarily for the convenience of internal NASA\nreaders. However, the RTOP, per se, may be of considerable interest\nto external users. See V, below.\n\nIX\n\nV. Source Code and RTOP\nThe last line of the citation (item 11) contains 1-3 sets of numbers in parenthesis. By interpreting the\ncoding a great deal of additional information on a project may be obtained. The first set is current\nand is the most useful; the second and third sets, if present, generally represent historical data.\nEach set of numbers is further divided into two groups separated by a blank space. The first group\ncontains source coding, while the second is the "Research and Technology Operating Plan" (RTOP).\n\nSource Coding (Item 1 la)\nThe first two-digit number identifies the NASA installation (by the code given in II,\nabove) which has most recently added funds to the project. Disagreement between this\ninstallation and the technical officer location usually indicates that responsibility for a\nproject is being transferred.\nThe second number identifies the major NASA Program Office responsible for the research,\nas follows: 200-299, Office of Technology Utilization; 300-399, Office of University Affairs;\n400-499, Office of Energy Programs; 500-599, Office of Tracking and Data Acquisition;\n600-699, Office of Applications; 700-799, Office of Aeronautics and Space Technology;\n800-899, Office of Space Science; and 900-999, Office of Manned Space Flight.\nRTOP (Item lib)\nThe RTOP, "Research and Technology Operating Plan," number indicates a broad technical\narea in which NASA desires to achieve certain objectives. Numerous projects, conducted\nboth in-house and out-of-house and with all classes of performers may contribute to the\nobjective of a single RTOP. Detailed descriptions of the RTOPs, including names of\nresponsible individuals and extensive cross-indexing.are published annually. The Research\nand Technology Operating Plan Summary may be purchased from the National Technical\nInformation Service (NTIS), Springfield, Virginia 22161.\n\nNASA\'S UNIVERSITY PROGRAM\n\nALABAMA\nNCR 01-001-003\nAlabama A&M University\n1000\nRadiation effects in the metabolism of phospho-lipids in the central\nnervous system of-albino rats\nObligations\nPeriod\n05/10/65-06/15/76\nFY75:\nTOTAL: $53,738\nPrtn. There may be a second technical officer, shown in the citation, at the same or a\ndifferent installation. Abbreviations used for locations are: ARC, Ames Research Center;\nFRC, Flight Research Center; GSFC, Goddard Space Flight Center; KSC, Kennedy Space\nCenter, JSC, Johnson Space Center; LARC, Langley Research Center; LERC, Lewis Research\nCenter; MSFC, Marshall Space Flight Center; National Space Technology Laboratories, NSTL;\nWFC, Wallops Flight Center and HQ, Headquarters. The HQ designator carries suffixed\nletters identifying individual Headquarters offices; and explanation of these identifiers and full\naddresses for all installations may be found in the prefatory pages. The key for the "Field\nCode" column is in Appendix B.\n\nTECH\nOFF\nLOC\n\nTECHNICAL\nOFFICER\nHaines, R. F.\nDanellis, J. V.\nHaughney, L. C.\nMiquel, J.\nHall, C. F.\nDyal, P.\nHowe, J.
